# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: naval-artillery
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] The **12-pounder long gun** was an intermediary calibre piece of artillery mounted on warships of the Age of Sail.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] They were used as main guns on the most typical frigates of the early 18th century, on the second deck of fourth-rate ships of the line, and on the upper decks or castles of 80-gun and 120-gun ships of the line.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] Naval 12-pounders were similar to 12-pound Army guns in the Gribeauval system: the canon lourd de 12 Gribeauval, used as a siege weapon, and the canon de 12 Gribeauval, which was considered a heavy field artillery piece.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] As the 12-pounder calibre was consistent with both the French and the British calibre systems, it was a widespread gun amongst nations between the 17th and the 19th century.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] Under Louis XIV, frigates were organised into "first-rank frigates", which were small two-deckers comparable in role to the 60-gun ships of the 19th century, and smaller "second-rank" frigates.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] The first-rank frigates carried the 12-pounder as main artillery on their lower deck.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] Later, under Louis XV, the frigate took its modern shape with a single artillery deck complemented by smaller pieces on the castles; new heavy frigates were developed to carry 26 12-pounders, with *Hermione* as the lead ship of the series.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] *Hermione* was captured by the British in 1757 and was swiftly imitated.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] A breakthrough towards fielding heavier guns was made in 1772, when the two units of the *Pourvoyeuse* class were built, with 24-pounders intended, but 18-pounders used in practice, and the 12-pounder remained the standard issue on most units.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] Under Louis XVI, the heavier 18-pounder frigate became predominant, with over 130 units produced, but the French Navy still had around 70 lighter 12-pounder frigates in commission.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] On 64-gun two-deckers, the 12-gun was used as secondary artillery, to supplement the 24-pounder main batteries.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] 28 guns were carried on the top gun-deck.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] Larger units used the 12-pounder to complement the firepower provided by their main and secondary artillery.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] On 80-gun ships of the *Tonnant* class and *Bucentaure* class, they armed the forecastle and the poop deck.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] On capital ships, the 12-pounder was used on the third deck from the reign of Louis XIV, with units like *Royal Louis* or *Soleil Royal* as typical examples.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] While the secondary artillery of these 100-gun ships evolved from 18-pounders to 24-pounders, the 12-pounder remained the standard gun on the third deck until 1803, when the *Océan*-class ship *Impérial* became the first 120-gun to carry 18-pounders on her third battery.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] In the Royal Navy, the 12-pounder was used in a similar capacity.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] The capture of *Hermione* in 1757 encouraged the British to imitate her design, yielding the *Southampton* and *Richmond*-class frigates.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] The 12-pounder also equipped the castles on razeed ships, where 12 pieces were mounted, and the 22-gun secondary battery of 50-gun fourth-rates.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] Finally, 30 were installed on the third deck of 90-gun second-rates.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] James mentions 4 12-pounder iron guns in the 1720s.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] 24 guns from the reigns of Queen Anne and King George I survive at Fort Prince of Wales in Hudson bay.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] They are either 9 1/2 ft long weighing between 33 1/2 and 35 cwt, 9 ft long weighing between 32 and 33 1/2 cwt, or 8 ft long weighing 33 1/4 cwt.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] The mensuration of 1743 gives the weight of the 9 ft 12-pounder gun as 32 hundredweight 2 quarter 3 pounds, and the dimensions there are almost identical with those in Adye's notebook of 1766.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] In 1780 Walton's notebook mentions, in addition to newer 12-pounders, a 9 1/2 ft gun of 34 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] The dimensions of this are very similar to those of Armstrong's construction in the early 1700s.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] Walton gives dimensions for these guns in his 1780 notebook, and where known, they are very similar to the earlier guns, with only minor differences.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] Both guns of 6 ft were intended exclusively for the land service, and by 1857 the gun of 6 ft 21 hundredweight was the only one mounted in service, presumably in the defense of ditches.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 8 1/2 ft 33 1/4 hundredweight was recommended for siege trains in 1844, as it could dismount artillery while requiring less weight of ammunition and powder than an 18- or 24-pounder gun.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] At the same time, the gun of 9 ft 34 3/4 hundredweight was recommended for sometimes replacing the 18-pounder in batteries where quick fire was required against storming parties or boat attacks.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] After the 1820s, the development of larger guns meant the iron 12-pounder declined in use, and in 1859 the Committee on Ordnance recommended that all iron 12-pounders except the gun of 6 ft be declared obsolete.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] In 1865 though, the guns of 9 and 8 1/2 ft were retained while all others were declared obsolete.
[src:naval-artillery/12-pounder-long-gun] "British Smooth-Bore Artillery: A Technological Study to Support Identification, Acquisition, Restoration, Reproduction, and Interpretation of Artillery at National Historic Parks in Canada" (PDF). pp.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] The **18-pounder long gun** was an intermediary calibre piece of naval artillery mounted on warships of the Age of Sail.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] They were used as main guns on the most typical frigates of the early 19th century, on the second deck of third-rate ships of the line, and even on the third deck of late first-rate ships of the line.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] As the 18-pounder calibre was consistent with both the French and the British calibre systems, it was used in many European navies between the 17th and the 19th century.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] It was a heavy calibre for early ships of the line, arming, for instance, the main batteries of *Couronne* in 1636.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] From the late 18th century, the French Navy used the 18-pounder in three capacities: as the main gun on frigates, as the battery on the upper gundeck of two-deckers, and lastly on the top deck of three-deckers.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] French frigates began carrying the 18-pounder under Louis XV, when the two *Pourvoyeuse*-class frigates, originally designed to carry 24-pounders, were equipped with it; at the time, a typical frigate would carry 12-pounders.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] Under Louis XVI, from 1779, the 18-pounder gradually became the standard calibre for frigates, starting with the *Hébé* class.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] These frigates were built on standard patterns designed by Jacques-Noël Sané, carrying 26, and later 28 main guns, complemented with smaller pieces on the forecastle.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] Around 130 of these frigates were built.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] At the end of the First French Empire, 24-pounder frigates began supplanting the 18-pounder frigates.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] Frigates built after the Bourbon Restoration used a different artillery system, one involving 30-pounders.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] On two-deckers, the 18-pounder was mounted on the upper deck as secondary artillery, to complement the 36-pounder main artillery on the lower deck.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] A 74-gun would carry thirty 18-pounders; this lighter secondary battery added firepower to the ship without raising the centre of gravity too much.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] Three-deckers used 36-pounders on their lower decks and 24-pounders on their second deck.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] During the First French Empire, 18-pounders would also arm Type 1 Model Towers for coastal defence.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] After introduction of rifled artillery in the middle 19th century, long 18-pounders were converted into so-called "14 cm n° 1 rifled muzzle-loaders Model 1864", by etching grooves on the inside of the barrel.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] James mentions 6 different 18-pounder guns in the early 1720s.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9 ft appears in a diagram from about 1735, where its weight was listed as 41 hundredweight 1 quarter 8 pounds.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] The 1743 mensuration contains an 18-pounder of the same length and weight, with very similar dimensions.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] In tests in Minorca, one of the 18-pounders used was 9 ft long and weighed 39 hundredweight 1 quarter 3 pounds.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] 3 guns of 9 feet length from the reign of George II (1727–1760) currently survive at the Gut of Digby in Nova Scotia.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] Their dimensions are similar to the gun in the 1735 diagram.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] Adye's notebook from 1766 has an 18-pounder of 9 ft with almost identical dimensions to that in the 1735 diagram and 1743 mensuration.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] The establishment of 1764 mentioned an 18-pounder gun of 9 ft and 40 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] Walton included a gun with this length and weight in his table of dimensions in 1780, with similar dimensions to the 9 ft gun in the 1743 mensuration and the 1766 notebook.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] Adye's manuals of 1801 and 1813 mention the 9 ft 40 hundredweight 18-pounder, though by then it was being superseded by the newer Blomefield guns.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9+1⁄2 ft is mentioned in Walton's table of dimensions in 1780, where its weight was 42 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] It also appears in Adye's manuals of 1801 and 1813, when it was also being superseded by Blomefield pattern guns.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 11 ft is first mentioned in tests in Minorca, where its weight was given as 51 hundredweight 5 pounds.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] In 1820, 6 iron 18-pounders are mentioned, with weights from 50 to 54+1⁄4 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] In 1857, an 18-pounder of 11 ft, "O.P" (old pattern) was in the list of guns submitted to the Committee on Ordnance.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] The guns of 9 feet 42+1⁄2 hundredweight and 8 feet 37+3⁄4 hundredweight were widely used as siege and garrison guns in addition to their naval role.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] As a siege gun, the 18-pounder served the same role as the Canon de 16 Gribeauval.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9 feet 42+1⁄2 hundredweight was used on the upper deck of 74-gun ships of the line.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 8 feet 37+3⁄4 hundredweight was used on the main deck of 46- and 42-gun frigates.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] In 1825 Mould noted the gun of 6 feet 27 hundredweight was "not used at present." Although the guns of 6 feet 20 hundredweight and 5+1⁄2 feet 15 hundredweight were bored-up from Blomefield guns, an 1865 report mentions that they were designed by Alexander Dickson (Blomefield's successor).
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] William Congreve designed an 18-pounder gun patterned after his 24-pounder gun, after the latter proved successful in trials in 1813.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] It was 6 feet 10 inches in length and 32 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] It had the same conical shape with more metal around the breech, and trunnions further to the rear.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] 8 pieces were mentioned in lists submitted to the Committee on Ordnance in 1857, though it may have only been experimental.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] The guns retained were Blomefield or Dickson pattern guns mentioned above, as were the guns of 6 feet and 7 feet to be abolished.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 6 feet 10 inches was a Congreve gun.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9 feet 40 hundredweight is not known, but it may have been the old 18-pounder of 9 feet from the establishment of 1764.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] The Royal Navy used the 18-pounder on frigates, which carried 28 guns.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] Fourth-rate ships carried 26 on their secondary batteries, and third rates carried 28.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] Unlike the French, the British used second rates, of 90 to 98 guns; the 90-gun vessels carried thirty 18-pounders on their middle deck, while the 98-gun vessels carried a total of sixty 18-pounders, distributed over both the second and the third deck.
[src:naval-artillery/18-pounder-long-gun] First rates carried thirty-four 18-pounders on their third deck and 24-pounders on the middle deck.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] The **24-pounder long gun** was a heavy calibre piece of artillery mounted on warships of the Age of Sail.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] 24-pounders were in service in the navies of France, Spain, Great Britain, the Netherlands, Sweden, and the United States.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] They were comparable to the Canon de 24 Gribeauval used by the French Army as its largest piece of siege artillery.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] 24-pounders were used as main guns on the heaviest frigates of the early 19th century and on fourth-rate ships of the line, on the second deck of first-rate ships of the line, and on the second deck of a few large third-rates.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] The 24-pounder calibre was consistent with both the French and the British calibre systems, and was a widespread gun amongst nations between the 17th and the 19th century.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] From the late 18th century, the French Navy used the 24-pounder in two capacities: as main gun on frigates and 64-guns, or as secondary artillery on three-deckers and even enlarged versions two-deckers.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] The experiment was tried again in 1785 with *Pomone*, a successful design that opened the way to a standardisation on the 24-pounder frigate exemplified by the *Romaine* class.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] Overall, 14 of these heavy frigates were built between *Pomone* in 1785, and *Poursuivante* in 1798, each carrying between 24 and 30 24-pounders.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] After the Bourbon Restoration, frigates were built using a different artillery system, carrying 30-pounders.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] Two-deckers used the 24-pounder in two capacities: on the smallest two-deckers of 64 guns, the 24-pounder constituted the main artillery, with 26 pieces.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] Typical 74-gun vessels carried a 36-pounder main battery and an 18-pounder secondary battery, until the enlarged variant of the *Téméraire* class appeared in 1803, comprising *Vétéran* and *Cassard*.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] More significantly, the 24-pounder armed the secondary battery of all 80-gun ships of the line from 1749, when the *Soleil-Royal* introduced the practice, resulting in a two-decker with enough firepower to challenge a three-decker of the time.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] During the reign of Louis XIV, three-deckers were standardised on a 36-pounder main artillery and an 18-pounder secondary battery.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] From the mid-18th century, under Louis XV, the secondary battery was strengthened to 24-pounders, beginning with the *Sans-Pareil* design that yielded *Royal Louis*.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] The other capital ships of the era, *Ville de Paris*, flagship of François Joseph Paul de Grasse during the American War of Independence, and *Bretagne*, flagship at the Battle of Ushant, similarly carried 24-pounders as secondary batteries.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] The practices was continued with the *Océan* class and the *Commerce de Paris* class.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] During the First French Empire, 24-pounders would also arm Type 1 Model Towers for coastal defence.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] In the Royal Navy, the 24-pounder was similarly used on some heavy frigates, which carried 26 guns.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] Fourth-rate ships carried 22 on their secondary batteries, and third-rates carried 32.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] First-rates carried thirty-four 24-pounders on their middle deck.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] Ten surviving guns which are likely examples of the 91⁄2-foot version weigh between 48 and 493⁄4 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] These guns are very similar to the gun of 91⁄2 feet and 491⁄4 hundredweight which was detailed in the mensuration of 1743.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] One other 24-pounder is mentioned in sources from 1780 and later, specifically a gun of 10 feet and 52 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] It is unknown whether the gun was new or the same as the 10 foot 24-pounder mentioned above.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] Except the guns of 501⁄2, 473⁄4, 22, and 20 hundredweight, most of these guns were little used, and declared obsolete in 1865 by the War Department.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] The guns cast in 1813 were designed to be evaluated against William Congreve's new pattern of gun.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] The guns of 91⁄2 feet 501⁄2 hundredweight and 9 feet 473⁄4 hundredweight were highly regarded as siege guns and widely used in that role in addition to their naval use.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] The guns of 22 and 20 hundredweight were mostly used in casemates and flank defenses as replacements for 24-pounder carronades.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] In response to a desire for lighter 24-pounders that could still be double-shotted,William Congreve designed a radical new type of 24-pounder, which was shorter, lighter, and with more metal concentrated around the gun breech rather than the chase (gun barrel).
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] It had a muzzle similar to a carronade, and the breeching ring was discarded in favor of a hole in the center of the neck of the cascabel.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] Because the weight of the cannon was much farther back, the trunnions could also be cast much farther rearward than in a similar conventional cannon.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] The heavier gun was tested in HMS *Eurotas* in October 1813, and the lighter gun was tested on HMS *Pactolus* in February 1814.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] The results were so favorable (despite somewhat violent recoil) that 300 more guns were ordered, and by 1820, Congreve noted 700 guns as being cast.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] Congreve also suggested several other guns to be constructed according to his principle, including a 24-pounder of 8 feet and 50 hundredweight.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] However, the recoil of the guns when in service proved to be worse than the trials indicated, and they were withdrawn from service by 1830, except in East India Company service.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] That year, 800 24-pounders were bored-up to produce 32-pounders, and they remained in active service in that role past 1865.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] Congreve's other suggested guns were never used beyond the testing stage.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] These were similar to the Blomefield designs, but with a slightly smaller caliber of 5.792 instead of 5.823 inches.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] In addition, a number of guns designated "N.P." for New Pattern appear in the records of the Committee on Ordnance.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] Finally, a 24-pounder of either 4 ft 10 in (1.47 m) or 5 ft (1.5 m) and 18 cwt was mentioned, and it was declared obsolete in 1865 by the War Department.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] Images are available showing 24-pounder long guns as the main gun deck armament on the USS *Independence* as used during the American Revolution; and the USS *Constitution* and USS *Constellation* as two of the original six frigates of the United States Navy starting in 1797.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] From the War of 1812 until the 1840s, The U.S.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] Navy used three classifications: the gun proper, which had a barrel weight of 150 lb (68 kg) per pound of shot, the double-fortified gun which had a barrel weight of 200 lb (91 kg) per pound of shot, and the medium gun, which had a barrel weight of 100 lb (45 kg) per pound of shot.
[src:naval-artillery/24-pounder-long-gun] By comparison, a carronade would have a barrel weight of 65 lb (29 kg) per pound of shot.
[src:naval-artillery/32-pounder-long-gun] The **demi-cannon** was a medium-sized cannon, similar to but slightly larger than a culverin and smaller than a regular 42 pounds (19 kg) cannon, developed in the early 17th century.
[src:naval-artillery/32-pounder-long-gun] A full cannon fired a 42-pound shot, but these were discontinued in the 18th century as they were seen as too unwieldy.
[src:naval-artillery/32-pounder-long-gun] The lower tiers of 18th century English warships were usually equipped with demi-cannons.
[src:naval-artillery/32-pounder-long-gun] Ships featuring demi-cannons included *Sovereign of the Seas*, *Resolution* and *James*, which fought in the Anglo-Dutch naval wars.
[src:naval-artillery/32-pounder-long-gun] Demi-cannons were also used on HMS *Stirling Castle*, the wreck of which was discovered in the Goodwin Sands.
[src:naval-artillery/32-pounder-long-gun] Several examples of this weapon were recovered from the site.
[src:naval-artillery/32-pounder-long-gun] The barrels of demi-cannon were typically 11 feet (3.4 m) long, had a calibre of 6 inches (150 mm) and could weigh up to 5,600 pounds (2,500 kg).
[src:naval-artillery/32-pounder-long-gun] It required 18 pounds (8.2 kg) of black powder to fire a 32 pounds (15 kg) round shot.
[src:naval-artillery/32-pounder-long-gun] The demi-cannon had an effective range of 1,600 feet (490 m).
[src:naval-artillery/32-pounder-long-gun] These 32-pounders were used during the 18th century on first-rate ships of the line which carried up to 100 guns.
[src:naval-artillery/32-pounder-long-gun] Though powerful, the naval demi-cannons were inaccurate, except at close range, which allowed warships to cause as much damage as possible.
[src:naval-artillery/32-pounder-long-gun] Sometimes a single broadside was enough to cripple the enemy vessel.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] The **36-pounder long gun** was the largest piece of artillery mounted on French warships of the Age of Sail.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] They were also used for coastal defense and fortification.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] They largely exceeded the heaviest guns fielded by the Army, which were 24-pounder long guns.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] The nominal weight of shot was 36 French *livres*, 17.6 kg (38.8 lb).
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] Installed on the lower deck of the larger warships, the 36-pounder long gun was the largest caliber used in the Navy of the Age of the Sail.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] Attempts to use 48-pounders were made, for instance on *Royal Louis*, but these proved impractical to use on ships, partly because their weight allowed for only a few pieces, and because the heavy balls were unwieldy to load by hand.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] However, some coastal batteries fielded 48-pounders and even 64-pounders.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] In the Royal Navy, a similar role was fulfilled by 32-pounder long guns.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] French warships began to carry 36-pounders under Louis XIV, with the reform of the Navy undertaken by Richelieu.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] At this time, only first rank warships could carry them.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] In 1676, the entire Navy fielded merely 64 such heavy pieces, all bronze.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] From 1690, in only two years, their number increased from 115 to 442 (of which 407 were made of bronze), as the number and size of first-rank ships increased.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] Many 12-pounders were melted to procure the bronze needed to produce the needed 36-pounders.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] A maximum was reached in 1702 with 860 guns (411 bronze and 449 iron).
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] Under Louis XV, their number was significantly reduced (164 in 1718, 452 in 1741), but from the mid-18th century, a sustained rearmament effort increased the number of 36-pounders to 986 in 1756, 1046 in 1777 and 2484 in 1786.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] They armed the lower battery of the largest warships: a 74-gun ship of the line would carry 28; an 80-gun, 30; and both 110-gun and 120-gun, 32.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] After the Napoleonic Wars, the 36-pounder long gun remained in use on older warships, though it was largely superseded by the 30-pounder long gun on newer units.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] The 36-pounders of the 1820s were fitted with flintlock primers, and those produced in this era featured a characteristic ring on the pommel.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] A 36-pounder required a 14-man crew, comprising one chief gunner, 12 gunners, and one powder boy.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] To load the piece, the first left-hand gunner would introduce a cartridge into the barrel; the first right-hand gunner would ram it to the bottom of the barrel; the first left-hand gunner would introduce the shot and a cloth wad, which would be rammed by the right-hand gunner.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] Then the crew would bring the gun to bear by pulling ropes.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] The chief gunner would then pin the cartridge through the touch hole and pour priming powder.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] The chief gunner would then point the gun with the help of the third and fourth gunners on each side, and the last gunner on the left would then fire the gun by touching the touch hole with a linstock.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] Flintlock firing was not standardized in the French navy before the end of the First Empire.
[src:naval-artillery/36-pounder-long-gun] The first right-hand gunner would then ram thrice to remove residues from the bore of the gun.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The **4.5 inch Mark 8** is a British naval gun system which currently equips the Royal Navy's destroyers and frigates, and some British destroyers and frigates sold to other countries.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] Guns with a 4.5 inch calibre have been the standard medium-calibre gun of the Royal Navy for use against surface, aircraft and shore targets since 1938.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The current 55-calibre Mark 8 gun replaced the World War II era 45-calibre QF 4.5-inch Mk I – V naval guns.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] Like all British 4.5 inch naval guns, it has a calibre of 4.45 inches (113 mm).
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] A new type of 4.5 inch gun with a longer 55-calibre barrel, it was designed in the 1960s for the Royal Navy's new classes of frigates and destroyers.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The weapon, built by Vickers Ltd Armament Division, was developed by the Royal Armament Research and Development Establishment using the Ordnance, QF 105 mm L13 of the Abbot self-propelled gun as a starting point (it used electrical primers).
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The outer shell of the gunhouse is built from glass-reinforced plastic (GRP).
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The new weapon emphasised reliability and rapid response to fire first round from shutdown state (particularly for defence against missiles) over a high rate of fire, allowing a switch to a lighter, single barrel mounting and ammunition of a one-piece design.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The gun system has a combination of electrical and hydraulic components and the full system penetrates up to three deck levels below the weather deck; deep magazine, gun control room and power room, gunbay and the gunhouse.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The weapon is semi-automatic and can be operated by a smaller crew than its predecessors.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] With no personnel in the gunhouse, loading is supported by personnel in the gunbay to load the feed ring and in the deep magazine to pass ammunition to the gunbay.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The captain of the gun in the control room ensures weapon readiness and the gun controller in the operations room aims and fires the weapon.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The gun has a rate of fire of about 25 rounds per minute and a range of 12 nmi (14 mi; 22 km) with the newer High Explosive Extended Range round.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The first recipient of the new gun and mount, the Mark 8, was the Iranian frigate *Zaal* in 1971.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The gun entered Royal Navy service in 1973 on the new destroyer *Bristol*.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] These guns proved to be less reliable than the older 4.5 inch Mark V gun (renamed Mark 6 gun mounting) during the Falklands War, being forced to cease fire on several occasions due to faults.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The first major modification to the mounting, the Mod 1, was developed in 1998 in two tranches replacing the gunhouse with a reduced radar cross section assembly and replacing the hydraulic loading mechanism with an all-electric system.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] This particular gun has been nicknamed the "Kryten gun" by members of Royal Navy, after the odd shaped head of a robot from the British Sci-fi comedy series *Red Dwarf*.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] Babcock upgraded 13 guns to Mod 1 standard between 2005 and 2012.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The guns are capable of operating in a fire support role against land or sea targets but according to *Navy Lookout*, software for the system is insufficient to support anti-aircraft missions.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] However, according to Alex Walters of Forces.net, it may be possible to use the 4.5-inch Mark 8 as an air defence weapon.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The Ministry of Defence investigated a proposal from BAE Systems to adapt the 4.5 inch system to accept the heavier calibre 155 mm (6.1 inch) gun barrel and breech from the AS-90 self-propelled gun.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] This "155mm Third Generation Maritime Fire Support" (155 TMF) would introduce a common gun calibre for the British Army and Royal Navy, helping with ammunition logistics, and encouraging joint Army-Navy development of extended range and precision guided shells.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] A £4m contract was awarded to develop a prototype, and firing trials were scheduled for 2009 with delivery in 2014, but the project was cancelled in the cuts implemented following the 2010 Strategic Defence and Security Review.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The Mk 8 was used in the Falklands War for naval gunfire support.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] The Type 21 frigate HMS Alacrity used her Mk 8 to sink the Argentine transport ARA Isla de los Estados.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] In 2011, HMS *Iron Duke* used Her Mk 8 gun to destroy a gun battery outside of the besieged town of Misrata, Libya, while *Liverpool* used its Mk 8 gun to destroy a shore battery that had fired missiles at her.
[src:naval-artillery/4-5-inch-mark-8-naval-gun] Although the Mk 8 was fitted to the Type 45 destroyer, on the Type 26 frigate it will be supplanted by the BAE 5-inch Mk 45 naval gun.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] These were built-up guns with an inner A tube, encased by a second tube, encased by a full length jacket.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Early guns were partially wire-wound, but later guns dispensed with the wire winding.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] The guns were breech loaded with two cloth bags of smokeless powder.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Third year type refers to the Welin breech block on this gun.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Breech block design began in 1914 AD, the third year of the *Taishō* period.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] This breech block design was also used on Japanese 41 cm (16.1 inch), 15.5 cm (6 inch), 14 cm (5.5 inch), 12.7 cm (5 inch), and 12 cm (4.7 inch) naval guns.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] The first model of this gun used a 32.63 kg (71.9 lb) powder charge to fire 7.87 in (200 mm) projectiles weighing 110 kg (242.5 lb) at a velocity of 870 m/s (2,854 ft/s).
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Useful life was 300 effective full charges (EFC) per gun.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] These guns were initially installed in type A low-angle (25°) single mounts aboard *Furutaka*-class cruisers, in type C (40°) twin turrets in the *Aoba* class, and in type D (40°) twin turrets in the *Myōkō* class.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Mark I guns can be visually distinguished from Mark II guns by an abrupt step in the chase diameter which was absent on the latter guns.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Second model guns used a 33.8 kg (74.5 lb) powder charge to fire 8 in (203.2 mm) projectiles weighing 125.85 kg (277.5 lb) at a velocity of 835 m/s (2,740 ft/s).
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] These guns had a useful life expectancy of 320 to 400 EFC (Effective/Equivalent Full Charge).
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Rate of fire varied from four rounds per minute firing at low angles diminishing to two or three rounds per minute firing at maximum elevation.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] These guns and the type E twin turret with 70-degree elevation installed on *Takao*-class cruisers were influenced by Royal Navy County-class cruisers.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Type E turrets were promptly redesigned to limit elevation to 55 degrees when 70-degree elevation proved impractical.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Modified type E turrets were installed as original equipment aboard *Maya* and the *Tone*-class cruisers, and replaced the original turrets aboard *Furutaka* and *Mogami*-class cruisers.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Mark II guns replaced the original Mark I guns in type C and D turrets so all Japanese heavy cruisers carried Mark II guns in twin turrets by December 1941.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Mark I guns were installed in casemates with a maximum elevation of 25 degrees limiting maximum range to 22 kilometers (14 mi).
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Aircraft carriers originally had four guns mounted in two type B twin turrets with a maximum elevation of 70 degrees.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] These were transferred to casemates in *Kaga* in 1934 and simply removed from *Akagi* in 1936.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Shell weights and muzzle velocities for high explosive or San Shiki incendiary shrapnel are specified for each of the Marks above.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Infobox muzzle velocity applies to type 91 armor-piercing (AP) shells with trajectory information below.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Illuminating shells were fired with a reduced charge at a muzzle velocity of 710 meters per second (2330 ft/sec).
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Only Mark I guns were installed in type A mounts.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Maximum elevation was 25° in the six single mounts installed aboard *Furutaka*-class cruisers in 1926, in the six casemate mountings installed on aircraft carriers *Akagi* in 1927 and *Kaga* in 1930, and in the four casemate mountings added to *Kaga* in 1934.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Only Mark I guns were installed in type B mounts.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Maximum elevation was 70° in the two twin turrets installed aboard *Akagi* in 1927 and *Kaga* in 1930.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] These turrets were removed from *Kaga* in 1934 and from *Akagi* in 1936.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Guns removed in 1934 were transferred to additional casemates aboard *Kaga*, but those removed in 1936 from *Akagi* were not replaced.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Three twin turrets with maximum elevation of 40° were installed only aboard *Aoba*-class cruisers.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] The Mark I guns installed in 1927 were replaced by Mark II guns in 1937 and 1938.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Five twin turrets with maximum elevation of 40° were installed only aboard *Myōkō*-class cruisers.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] The Mark I guns installed in 1928 and 1929 were replaced by Mark II guns between 1931 and 1934.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Only Mark II guns were installed in type E twin turrets.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Maximum elevation was 70° in the five turrets installed aboard *Atago*, *Takao*, and *Chōkai* in 1932.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Early recognition of the impracticality of using these guns for anti-aircraft fire caused reduction of maximum elevation to 55° in all subsequent installations.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] *Maya* received five 55° turrets as original equipment in 1932.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Three new turrets with Mark I guns from *Haguro* and *Ashigara* re-bored to Mark II (as there was a shortage of Mark II guns at this time) replaced the original type A mounts aboard *Furutaka*-class cruisers in 1936 and 1937.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] *Tone*-class cruisers were completed with four type E turrets in 1937 and 1938.
[src:naval-artillery/50-3rd-year-type-naval-gun] Five new turrets replaced the original triple 6-inch turrets aboard *Mogami* class cruisers between 1939 and 1941.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The idea of ship-borne artillery dates back to the classical era.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Julius Caesar wrote about the Roman navy's usage of ship-borne catapults against Celtic Britons ashore in his *Commentarii de Bello Gallico*.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The dromons of the Byzantine Empire carried catapults and Greek fire.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] From the Middle Ages onwards, warships began to carry cannons of various calibres.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In the Battle of Tangdao in 1161, the Southern Song general Li Bao used huopao (a type of gunpowder weapons, possibly cannons) and fire arrows against the Jin dynasty fleets.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The Mongol invasion of Java introduced cannons, to be used in Song dynasty naval general warfare (e.g.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The Battle of Arnemuiden, fought between England and France in 1338 at the start of the Hundred Years' War, was the first recorded European naval battle using artillery.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The English ship *Christopher* was armed with three cannons and one hand gun.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In Asia naval artillery are recorded from the Battle of Lake Poyang in 1363 and in considerable quantities at the Battle of Jinpo in 1380 with cannon made by Ch'oe Mu-sŏn.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] 80 Koryo warships successfully repelled 500 Japanese pirates referred to as Wokou using long range cannon fire.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] By the 15th century, most Mediterranean powers were utilising heavy cannon mounted on the bow or stern of a vessel and designed to bombard fortresses on shore.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] By mid-century some vessels also carried smaller broadside cannon for bombarding other vessels immediately prior to an attempted boarding.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] These small guns were anti-personnel weapons and were fired at point blank range to accompany engagement with muskets or bows.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In the 1470s, the Portuguese and Venetian navies were experimenting with ship mounted cannons as anti-ship weapons.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] King John II of Portugal, while still a prince in 1474, is credited with pioneering the introduction of a reinforced deck on the old Henry-era caravel to allow the mounting of heavy guns for this purpose.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] These were initially wrought iron breech-loading weapons known as basilisks.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In 1489 he further contributed to the development of naval artillery by establishing the first standardized teams of trained naval gunners (*bombardeiros*).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Use of naval artillery expanded toward the end of the 15th century, with ships purpose-built to carry dozens of small bore breech-loading anti-personnel guns.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] English examples of these types include Henry VII's *Regent* and *Sovereign*, with 141 and 225 guns respectively.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Elsewhere in late medieval Northern Europe, the Dutch-built flagship of the Danish-Norwegian King Hans, *Gribshunden*, carried 68 guns.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Eleven gun beds from *Gribshunden*'s artillery have been recovered by archaeologists; all of the guns were small bore swivel guns firing composite lead/iron shot about the size of a golf ball.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The remains of at least three more guns are still on that wreck; two of them still have some of the wrought iron barrels and powder chambers evident.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] By the early 16th century, the navies of the Mediterranean had universally adopted lighter and more accurate muzzleloaders, cast in bronze and capable of firing balls or stones weighing up to 60 lb (27 kg).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The 16th century was an era of transition in naval warfare.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Since ancient times, war at sea had been fought much like that on land: with melee weapons and bows and arrows, but on floating wooden platforms rather than battlefields.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Though the introduction of guns was a significant change, it only slowly changed the dynamics of ship-to-ship combat.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] As guns became heavier and able to take more powerful gunpowder charges, they needed to be placed lower in the ship, closer to the water line.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Heavy artillery on galleys was mounted in the bow, which aligned easily with the long-standing tactical tradition of attacking head on, bow first.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The ordnance on galleys was heavy from its introduction in the 1480s, and capable of quickly demolishing the high, thin medieval stone walls that still prevailed in the 16th century.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] This temporarily upended the strength of older seaside fortresses, which had to be rebuilt to cope with gunpowder weapons.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The addition of guns also improved the amphibious abilities of galleys as they could make assaults supported with heavy firepower, and were even more effectively defended when beached stern-first.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Gunports cut in the hull of ships were introduced as early as 1501, about a decade before the famous Tudor era ship, the *Mary Rose*, was built.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] This made broadsides, coordinated volleys from all the guns on one side of a ship, possible for the first time in history, at least in theory.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Ships such as *Mary Rose* carried a mixture of cannon of different types and sizes, many designed for land use, and using incompatible ammunition at different ranges and rate of fire.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] *Mary Rose*, like other ships of the time, was built during a period of rapid development of heavy artillery, and her armament was a mix of old designs and innovations.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The heavy armament was a mix of older-type wrought iron and cast bronze guns, which differed considerably in size, range and design.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The large iron guns were made up of staves or bars welded into cylinders and then reinforced by shrinking iron hoops and breech loaded, and equipped with simpler gun-carriages made from hollowed-out elm logs with only one pair of wheels, or without wheels entirely.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The bronze guns were cast in one piece and rested on four-wheel carriages which were essentially the same as those used until the 19th century.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The breech-loaders were cheaper to produce and both easier and faster to reload, but could take less powerful charges than cast bronze guns.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The majority of the guns were small iron guns with short range that could be aimed and fired by a single person.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Though the design is unknown, there were two *top pieces* in a 1546 inventory (finished after the sinking) which was probably similar to a base, but placed in one or more of the fighting tops.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] During rebuilding in 1536, *Mary Rose* had a second tier of carriage-mounted long guns fitted.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Records show how the configuration of guns changed as gun-making technology evolved and new classifications were invented.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In 1514, the armament consisted mostly of anti-personnel guns like the larger breech-loading iron *murderers* and the small *serpentines*, *demi-slings* and stone guns.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Only a handful of guns in the first inventory were powerful enough to hole enemy ships, and most would have been supported by the ship's structure rather than resting on carriages.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The inventories of both the *Mary Rose* and the Tower had changed radically by 1540.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] There were now the new cast bronze *cannons*, *demi-cannons*, *culverins* and *sakers* and the wrought iron *port pieces* (a name that indicated they fired through ports), all of which required carriages, had longer range and were capable of doing serious damage to other ships.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Various types of ammunition could be used for different purposes: plain spherical shot of stone or iron smashed hulls, spiked bar shot and shot linked with chains would tear sails or damage rigging, and canister shot packed with sharp flints produced a devastating shotgun effect.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Trials made with replicas of culverins and port pieces showed that they could penetrate wood the same thickness of the *Mary Rose*'s hull planking, indicating a stand-off range of at least 90 m (100 yd).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The port pieces proved particularly efficient at smashing large holes in wood when firing stone shot and were a devastating anti-personnel weapon when loaded with flakes or pebbles.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] A perrier threw a stone projectile about 1,200 metres (3⁄4 miles), while a cannon threw a 32-pound ball 1,600 metres (a full mile), and a culverin a 17-pound ball 2 kilometres (1+1⁄4 miles).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Swivel guns and smaller cannon were often loaded with grapeshot for antipersonnel use at closer ranges, while the larger cannon might be loaded with a single heavy cannonball to cause structural damage.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In Portugal, the development of the heavy galleon removed even the necessity of bringing carrack firepower to bear in most circumstances.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] One of them became famous in the conquest of Tunis in 1535, and could carry 366 bronze cannon (a possible exaggeration of the various European chroniclers of the time, that reported this number; or also possibly counting the weapons in reserve).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] This ship had an exceptional capacity of fire for its time, illustrating the evolution that was operating at the time, and for this reason, it became known as *Botafogo*, meaning literally 'fire maker', 'torcher', or 'spitfire' in popular Portuguese.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Naval artillery and tactics stayed relatively constant during the period 1571–1862, with large, sail-powered wooden naval warships mounting a great variety of different types and sizes of cannon as their main armament.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] By the 1650s, the line of battle had developed as a tactic that could take advantage of the broadside armament.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] This method became the heart of naval warfare during the Age of Sail, with navies adapting their strategies and tactics in order to get the most broadside-on fire.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Cannon were mounted on multiple decks to maximise broadside effectiveness.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Numbers and calibre differed somewhat with preferred tactics.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] France and Spain attempted to immobilize ships by destroying rigging with long-range, accurate fire from their swifter and more maneuverable ships, while England and the Dutch Republic favoured rapid fire at close range to shatter a ship's hull and disable its crew.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] A typical broadside of a Royal Navy ship of the late 18th century could be fired two or three times in approximately 5 minutes, depending on the training of the crew, a well trained one being essential to the simple yet detailed process of preparing to fire.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] French and Spanish crews typically took twice as long to fire an aimed broadside.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] An 18th-century ship of the line typically mounted 32-pounder or 36-pounder long guns on a lower deck, and 18- or 24-pounders on an upper deck, with some 12-pounders on the forecastle and quarterdeck.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] From the late sixteenth century it was routine for naval ships to carry a master gunner, responsible for overseeing the operation of the cannon on board.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Originally a prestigious position, its status declined throughout the Age of Sail as responsibility for gunnery strategy was devolved to midshipmen or lieutenants.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] By the eighteenth century the master gunner had become responsible only for the maintenance of the guns and their carriages, and for overseeing supplies of gunpowder and shot.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In status the master gunner remained equal to the boatswain and ship's carpenter as senior warrant officers, and was entitled to the support of one or more gunner's mates.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In the Royal Navy, the master gunner also directed the "quarter gunners", able seamen with the added responsibility of managing the rate and direction of fire from any set of four gun crews.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The British Admiralty did not see fit to provide additional powder to captains to train their crews, generally only allowing one-third of the powder loaded onto the ship to be fired in the first six months of a typical voyage, barring hostile action.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Instead of live fire practice, most captains exercised their crews by "running" the guns in and outperforming all the steps associated with firing but for the actual discharge.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Some wealthy captains – those who had made money capturing prizes or from wealthy families – were known to purchase powder with their own funds to enable their crews to fire real discharges at real targets.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Firing a naval cannon required a great amount of labour and manpower.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The propellant was gunpowder, whose bulk had to be kept in a special storage area below deck for safety.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] *Powder boys* (sometimes called *powder monkeys*), typically 10–14 years old, were enlisted to run powder from the armoury up to the gun decks of a vessel as required.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] A wet swab was used to mop out the interior of the barrel, extinguishing any embers from a previous firing which might set off the next charge of gunpowder prematurely.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Gunpowder, either loose or in a cloth or parchment cartridge pierced by a metal *pricker* through the touch hole, was placed in the barrel and followed by a cloth wad (typically made from canvas and old rope), then rammed home with a rammer.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] This took the majority of the guncrew manpower as the total weight of a large cannon in its carriage could reach over two tons, and the ship would probably be rolling.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The touch hole in the rear (*breech*) of the cannon was primed with finer gunpowder (*priming powder*), or a quill (from a porcupine or such, or the skin-end of a feather) pre-filled with priming powder, then ignited.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The earlier method of firing a cannon was to apply a linstock – a wooden staff holding a length of smoldering match at the end—to the touch-hole of the gun.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] This was dangerous and made accurate shooting from a moving ship difficult, as the gun had to be fired from the side, to avoid its recoil, and there was a noticeable delay between the application of the linstock and the gun firing.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In 1745, the British began using *gunlocks* (flintlock mechanisms fitted to cannon).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The gunlock was operated by pulling a cord, or lanyard.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The gun-captain could stand behind the gun, safely beyond its range of recoil, and sight along the barrel, firing when the roll of the ship lined the gun up with the enemy and so avoid the chance of the shot hitting the sea or flying high over the enemy's deck.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Despite their advantages, gunlocks spread gradually as they could not be retrofitted to older guns.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The British adopted them faster than the French, who had still not generally adopted them by the time of the Battle of Trafalgar in 1805, placing them at a disadvantage as they were in general use by the Royal Navy at this time.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] After the introduction of gunlocks, linstocks were retained, but only as a backup means of firing.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The linstock slow match, or the spark from the flintlock, ignited the priming powder, which in turn set off the main charge, which propelled the shot out of the barrel.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] When the gun discharged, the recoil sent it backwards until it was stopped by the breech rope – a sturdy rope made fast to ring bolts set into the bulwarks, and a turn taken about the gun's cascabel, the knob at the end of the gun barrel.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The types of artillery used varied from nation and time period.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The more important types included the demi-cannon, the culverin and demi-culverin, and the carronade.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] One descriptive characteristic which was commonly used was to define guns by their 'pound' rating: theoretically, the weight of a single solid iron shot fired by that bore of cannon.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Common sizes were 42-pounders, 36-pounders, 32-pounders, 24-pounders, 18-pounders, 12-pounders, 9-pounders, 8-pounders, 6-pounders, and various smaller calibres.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] French ships used standardized guns of 36-pound, 24-pound, and 12-pound calibres, augmented by smaller pieces.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In general, larger ships carrying more guns carried larger ones as well.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The muzzle-loading design and weight of the iron placed design constraints on the length and size of naval guns.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Muzzle loading required the cannon muzzle to be positioned within the hull of the ship for loading.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The hull is only so wide, with guns on both sides, and hatchways in the centre of the deck also limit the room available.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Weight is always a great concern in ship design as it affects speed, stability, and buoyancy.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The desire for longer guns for greater range and accuracy, and greater weight of shot for more destructive power, led to some interesting gun designs.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] It was a proportionately longer-barrelled 9-pounder.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Its typical mounting as a bow or stern chaser, where it was not perpendicular to the keel, allowed room to operate this longer weapon.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In a chase situation, the gun's greater range came into play.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] However, the desire to reduce weight in the ends of the ship and the relative fragility of the bow and stern portions of the hull limited this role to a 9-pounder, rather than one which used a 12- or 24-pound shot.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In the reign of Queen Elizabeth advances in manufacturing technology allowed the English Navy Royal to start using matched cannon firing standard ammunition, allowing firing of coordinated broadsides (although that was more of a matter of improved training and discipline than of matched guns).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Different types of shot were employed for various situations.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Standard fare was the round shot, which is spherical cast-iron shot used for smashing through the enemy's hull, holing his waterline, smashing gun carriages and breaking masts and yards, with a secondary effect of sending large wooden splinters flying about to maim and kill the enemy crew.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] At very close range, two round shots could be loaded in one gun and fired together.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] *Double-shotting*, as it was called, lowered the effective range and accuracy of the gun, but could be devastating within pistol shot range.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Canister shot consisted of metallic canisters which broke open upon firing, each of which was filled with hundreds of lead musket balls for clearing decks like a giant shotgun blast; it is commonly mistakenly called *grapeshot*, both today and in historic accounts (typically those of landsmen).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Although canister shot could be used aboard ship, it was more traditionally an army artillery projectile for clearing fields of infantry.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The name "grapeshot" comes from the former's apparent resemblance to a bunch of grapes.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] When fired, the inertial forces would cause the bundle to disintegrate, and the shot would spread out to hit numerous targets.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Grapeshot was a naval weapon, and existed for almost as long as naval artillery.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The larger size of the grapeshot projectiles was desirable because it was more capable of cutting thick cordage and smashing equipment than the relatively smaller musket balls of a canister shot, although it could rarely penetrate a wooden hull.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Although grapeshot won great popular fame as a weapon used against enemy crew on open decks (especially when massed in great numbers, such as for a boarding attempt), it was originally designed and carried primarily for cutting up enemy rigging.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] A more specialized shot for similar use was the chain-shot, which consisted of two iron balls joined together with a chain, and was particularly designed for cutting large swaths of rigging, such as boarding nets and sails.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] It was far more effective than other projectiles in this use, but was of little use for any other purpose.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] *Bar shot* was similar, except that it used a solid bar to join the two balls; the bar could sometimes also extend upon firing.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Series of long chain links were also used in a similar way.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In China and other parts of Asia, fire arrows were thick, dartlike, rocket-propelled incendiary projectiles with barbed points, wrapped with pitch-soaked canvas which took fire when the rocket was launched, which could either be from special launching racks or from a cannon barrel .
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The point stuck in sails, hulls or spars and set fire to the enemy ship.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In Western naval warfare, shore forts sometimes heated iron shot red-hot in a special furnace before loading it (with water-soaked wads to prevent it from setting off the powder charge prematurely.) The hot shot lodging in a ship's dry timbers would set the ship afire.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The bomb ketch was developed as a wooden sailing naval ship with its primary armament as mortars mounted forward near the bow and elevated to a high angle, and projecting their fire in a ballistic arc.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Explosive shells or carcasses were employed rather than solid shot.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Bomb vessels were specialized ships designed for bombarding (hence the name) fixed positions on land.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The first recorded deployment of bomb vessels by the English was for the Siege of Calais in 1347 when Edward III deployed single deck ships with Bombardes and other artillery.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The first specialised bomb vessels were built towards the end of the 17th century, based on the designs of Bernard Renau d'Eliçagaray, and used by the French Navy.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Five such vessels were used to shell Algiers in 1682 destroying the land forts, and killing some 700 defenders.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Two years later the French repeated their success at Genoa.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The early French bomb vessels had two forward-pointing mortars fixed side-by-side on the foredeck.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] To aim these weapons, the entire ship was rotated by letting out or pulling in a spring anchor.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The range was usually controlled by adjusting the gunpowder charge.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The Royal Navy continued to refine the class over the next century or more, after Huguenot exiles brought designs over to England and the United Provinces.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The side-by-side, forward-pointing mortars were replaced in the British designs by mortars mounted on the centerline on revolving platforms.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] These platforms were supported by strong internal wooden framework to transmit the forces of firing the weapons to the hull.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The interstices of the framework were used as storage areas for ammunition.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Early bomb vessels were rigged as ketches with two masts.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] They were awkward vessels to handle, in part because bomb ketches typically had the masts stepped farther aft than would have been normal in other vessels of similar rig, in order to accommodate the mortars forward and provide a clear area for their forward fire.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] As a result, the 19th century British bomb vessels were designed as full-rigged ships with three masts, and two mortars, one between each neighboring pair of masts.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The art of gunnery was put on a scientific basis in the mid-18th century.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] British military engineer Benjamin Robins used Newtonian mechanics to calculate the projectile trajectory while taking the air resistance into account.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] He also carried out an extensive series of experiments in gunnery, embodying his results in his famous treatise on gunnery *New Principles in Gunnery* (1742), which contains a description of his ballistic pendulum .
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Robins also made a number of important experiments on the resistance of the air to the motion of projectiles, and on the force of gunpowder, with computation of the velocities thereby communicated to projectiles.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] He compared the results of his theory with experimental determinations of the ranges of mortars and cannon, and gave practical maxims for the management of artillery.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] He also made observations on the flight of rockets and wrote on the advantages of rifled gun barrels.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Robins argued for the use of larger bore cannon and the importance of tightly fitting cannonballs.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] His work on gunnery was translated into German by Leonhard Euler and was heavily influential on the development of naval weaponry across Europe.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Another significant scientific gunnery book was written by Warrant Officer George Marshall, a Master Gunner in the United Navy.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] He wrote *Marshall's Practical Marine Gunnery* in 1822.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The book discusses the dimensions and apparatus necessary for the equipment of naval artillery.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The book goes into further details regarding the distance of a shot on a ship based on the sound of the gun, which was found to fly at a rate of 348 metres (1,142 feet; 381 yards) in one second.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] According to Marshall's equation after seeing the flash of a cannon and hearing the blast the gunner would count the seconds until impact.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] This way a trained ear would know the distance a cannonball traveled and might gain information or return fire.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The book example, outlines a 9-second scenario where the distance the cannon was fired from the gunner was approximately 3,133 metres (10,278 feet; 3,426 yards).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] By the outbreak of the French Revolutionary Wars in 1793, a series of technical innovations over the course of the late 18th century combined to give the British fleet a distinct superiority over the ships of the French and Spanish navies.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The carronade was a short-barrelled gun which threw a heavy ball developed by the Carron Company, a Scottish ironworks, in 1778.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Because of irregularities in the size of cannonballs and the difficulty of boring out gun barrels, there was usually a considerable gap between the ball and the bore – often as much as 6 mm (1⁄4 inch) – with a consequent loss of efficiency.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The manufacturing practices introduced by the Carron Company reduced the windage considerably, enabling the ball to be fired with less powder and hence a smaller and lighter gun.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The carronade was half the weight of an equivalent long gun, but could throw a heavy ball over a limited distance.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The light weight of the carronade meant that the guns could be added to the forecastle and quarterdeck of frigates and ships of the line, increasing firepower without affecting the ship's sailing qualities.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] It became known as the "Smasher" and gave ships armed with carronades a great advantage at short range.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The mounting, attached to the side of the ship on a pivot, took the recoil on a slider.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The reduced recoil did not alter the alignment of the gun.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The smaller gunpowder charge reduced the guns' heating in action.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The pamphlet advocated the use of woollen cartridges, which, although more expensive, eliminated the need for wadding and worming.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Simplifying gunnery for comparatively untrained merchant seamen in both aim and reloading was part of the rationale for the gun.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The replacement of trunnions by a bolt underneath, to connect the gun to the mounting, reduced the width of the carriage enhancing the wide angle of fire.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] A carronade weighed one-quarter as much and used one-quarter to one-third of the gunpowder charge for a long gun firing the same cannonball.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Its invention is variously ascribed to Lieutenant General Robert Melville in 1759, or to Charles Gascoigne, manager of the Carron Company from 1769 to 1779.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Carronades initially became popular on British merchant ships during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] A lightweight gun that needed only a small gun crew and was devastating at short range was a weapon well suited to defending merchant ships against French and American privateers.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In the Action of 4 September 1782, the impact of a single carronade broadside fired at close range by the frigate HMS *Rainbow* under Henry Trollope caused a wounded French captain to capitulate and surrender the *Hébé* after a short fight.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Flintlock firing mechanisms for cannon were suggested by Captain Sir Charles Douglas and introduced during the American War of Independence in place of the traditional matches.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Flintlocks enabled a higher rate of fire and greater accuracy as the gun captain could choose the exact moment of firing.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Prior to this the Royal Navy introduced the use of goose quills filled with powder during the Seven Years' War giving an almost instantaneous burn time compared with earlier methods of detonation.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Douglas also innovated a system that greatly increased the field of fire.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] By the simple expedient of attaching the gun ropes at a greater distance from the gunports, the range through which each cannon could be traversed was greatly improved.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The new system was first tested at the Battle of the Saintes in 1782, where HMS *Duke*, *Formidable*, and *Arrogant*, and perhaps other British ships, had adopted Douglas's new system.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The shrapnel shell was developed in 1784, by Major General Henry Shrapnel of the Royal Artillery.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Canister shot was already in widespread use at the time; a tin or canvas container filled with small iron or lead balls burst open when fired, giving the effect of an oversized shotgun shell.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] Shrapnel's innovation was to combine the multi-projectile shotgun effect of canister shot, with a time fuze to open the canister and disperse the bullets it contained at some distance along the canister's trajectory from the gun.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] His shell was a hollow cast-iron sphere filled with a mixture of balls and powder, with a crude time fuze.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] If the fuze was set correctly then the shell would break open, either in front or above the intended target, releasing its contents (of musket balls).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] The shrapnel balls would carry on with the "remaining velocity" of the shell.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p01] In addition to a denser pattern of musket balls, the retained velocity could be higher as well, since the shrapnel shell as a whole would likely have a higher ballistic coefficient than the individual musket balls .
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The Industrial Revolution introduced steam-powered ironclad warships seemingly impervious to cast cannon.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The inadequacy of naval artillery caused the naval ram to reappear as a means of sinking armored warships.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The rapidity of innovation through the last half of the 19th century caused some ships to be obsolete before they were launched.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Maximum projectile velocity obtainable with gunpowder in cast cannon was approximately 480 m/s (1,600 ft/s).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Increased projectile weight through increased caliber was the only method of improving armor penetration with this velocity limitation.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Some ironclads carried extremely heavy, slow-firing guns of calibres up to 16.25 inches (41.3 cm).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] These guns were the only weapons capable of piercing the ever-thicker iron armour on the later ironclads, but required steam powered machinery to assist loading cannonballs too heavy for men to lift.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Explosive shells had long been in use in ground warfare (in howitzers and mortars), but they were only fired at high angles and with relatively low velocities.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Shells are inherently dangerous to handle, and no solution had been found to combine the explosive character of the shells with the high power and flatter trajectory of a high velocity gun.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] However, high trajectories were not practical for marine combat and naval combat essentially required flat-trajectory guns in order to have some decent odds of hitting the target.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Therefore, naval warfare had consisted for centuries of encounters between flat-trajectory cannon using inert cannonballs, which could inflict only local damage even on wooden hulls.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The first naval gun designed to fire explosive shells was the Paixhans gun, developed by the French general Henri-Joseph Paixhans in 1822–1823.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] He advocated using flat-trajectory shell guns against warships in 1822 in his *Nouvelle force maritime et artillerie*, and developed a delaying mechanism which, for the first time, allowed shells to be fired safely in high-powered flat-trajectory guns.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The effect of explosive shells lodging into wooden hulls and then detonating was potentially devastating.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] This was first demonstrated by Henri-Joseph Paixhans in trials against the two-decker *Pacificateur* in 1824, in which he successfully broke up the ship.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Two prototype Paixhans guns had been cast in 1823 and 1824 for this test.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Paixhans reported the results in *Experiences faites sur une arme nouvelle*.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The shells were equipped with a fuse which ignited automatically when the gun was fired.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The shell would then lodge itself in the wooden hull of the target before exploding a moment later.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The first Paixhans guns for the French Navy were manufactured in 1841.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The barrel of the guns weighed about 10,000 lbs.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] (4.5 metric tons), and proved accurate to about two miles.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] In the 1840s, Britain, Russia and the United States adopted the new naval guns.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The effect of the guns in an operational context was decisively demonstrated during the Crimean War.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The incendiary properties of exploding shells demonstrated the obsolescence of wooden warships in the 1853 Battle of Sinop; but detonation effectiveness was limited by use of gunpowder bursting charges.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Early high explosives used in torpedo warheads would detonate during the acceleration of firing from a gun.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] After brief use of dynamite guns aboard USS *Vesuvius*, picric acid became widely used in conventional naval artillery shells during the 1890s.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] William Armstrong was awarded a contract by the British government in the 1850s to design a revolutionary new piece of artillery—the Armstrong Gun—produced at the Elswick Ordnance Company.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] This marked the birth of modern artillery both on land and at sea.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The piece was rifled, which allowed for a much more accurate and powerful action.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The necessary machinery to accurately rifle artillery was only available by the mid-19th century.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The cast iron shell fired by the Armstrong gun was similar in shape to a Minié ball and had a thin lead coating which made it fractionally larger than the gun's bore and which engaged with the gun's rifling grooves to impart spin to the shell.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] This spin, together with the elimination of windage as a result of the tight fit, enabled the gun to achieve greater range and accuracy than existing smooth-bore muzzle-loaders with a smaller powder charge.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Although attempts at breech-loading mechanisms had been made since medieval times, the essential engineering problem was that the mechanism couldn't withstand the explosive charge.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] It was only with the advances in metallurgy and precision engineering capabilities during the Industrial Revolution that Armstrong was able to construct a viable solution.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The gun combined all the properties that make up an effective artillery piece.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The gun was mounted on a carriage in such a way as to return the gun to firing position after the recoil.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] What made the gun really revolutionary lay in the technique of the construction of the gun barrel that allowed it to withstand much more powerful explosive forces.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The "built-up" method involved assembling the barrel with wrought-iron (later mild steel was used) tubes of successively larger diameter.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The next tube would be heated to allow it to expand and fit over the previous tube.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] When it cooled the tube would contract to a slightly smaller diameter, which allowed an even pressure along the walls of the gun which was directed inward against the outward forces that the gun firing exerted on the barrel.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Built-up guns with rifling made cast cannon obsolete by 1880.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Armstrong's system was adopted in 1858, initially for "special service in the field" and initially he only produced smaller artillery pieces, 6-pounder (2.5 in/64 mm) mountain or light field guns, 9-pounder (3 in/76 mm) guns for horse artillery, and 12-pounder (3 inches /76 mm) field guns.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] However, despite the gun's advantages, an 1863 Ordnance Select committee decided to revert to muzzle-loading artillery pieces on the grounds of cost and efficiency.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Large-caliber breech-loading naval artillery became practical with French development of the interrupted screw obturator by Charles Ragon de Bange in 1872.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] It was only after a serious accident on board HMS *Thunderer* in 1879 when the left muzzleloading 12-inch (305 mm) gun in the forward turret exploded during practice firing in the Sea of Marmora killing 11 and injuring a further 35, that the Royal Navy decisively changed to breech loading guns.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Improved loading and handling procedures were also adopted, and Thunderer herself was re-equipped with long-calibre 10" breech-loaders.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Breech loading artillery overcame barrel length limitations of cast cannon imposed by the necessity of retracting the cannon into the hull for reloading through the muzzle.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Simultaneous availability of longer barrels and slower burning brown powder increased projectile velocities to 650 m/s (2,100 ft/s).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Spin-stabilized elongated projectiles offered both reliable positioning of percussion fuzes and improved armor penetration through increased sectional density.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Before the development of large-calibre, long-range guns in the mid-19th century, the classic battleship design used rows of port-mounted guns on each side of the ship, often mounted in casemates.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Firepower was provided by a large number of guns which could only be aimed in a limited arc from one side of the ship.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Due to instability, fewer larger and heavier guns can be carried on a ship.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Also, the casemates often sat near the waterline, which made them vulnerable to flooding and restricted their use to calm seas.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Turrets were weapon mounts designed to protect the crew and mechanism of the artillery piece and with the capability of being aimed and fired in many directions as a rotating weapon platform.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] This platform can be mounted on a fortified building or structure such as an anti-naval land battery, or on a combat vehicle, a naval ship, or a military aircraft.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] During the Crimean War, Captain Cowper Phipps Coles constructed a raft with guns protected by a 'cupola' and used the raft, named *Lady Nancy*, to shell the Russian town of Taganrog in the Black Sea.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] *Lady Nancy* "proved a great success", and Coles patented his rotating turret after the war.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Following Coles' patenting, the British Admiralty ordered a prototype of Coles' design in 1859, which was installed in the floating battery vessel, HMS *Trusty*, for trials in 1861, becoming the first warship to be fitted with a revolving gun turret.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Coles' design aim was to create a ship with the greatest possible all round arc of fire, as low in the water as possible to minimise the target.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The Admiralty accepted the principle of the turret gun as a useful innovation, and incorporated it into other new designs.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Coles submitted a design for a ship having ten domed turrets each housing two large guns.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The design was rejected as impractical, although the Admiralty remained interested in turret ships and instructed its own designers to create better designs.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Coles enlisted the support of Prince Albert, who wrote to the first Lord of the Admiralty, the Duke of Somerset, supporting the construction of a turret ship.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] In January 1862, the Admiralty agreed to construct a ship, HMS *Prince Albert*, which had four turrets and a low freeboard, intended only for coastal defence.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Coles was allowed to design the turrets, but the ship was the responsibility of the chief Constructor Isaac Watts.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Another of Coles' designs, HMS *Royal Sovereign*, was completed in August 1864.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Its existing broadside guns were replaced with four turrets on a flat deck and the ship was fitted with 5.5 inches (140 mm) of armour in a belt around the waterline.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Early ships like *Monitor* and *Royal Sovereign* had little sea-keeping qualities, being limited to coastal waters.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Coles, in collaboration with Sir Edward James Reed, went on to design and build HMS *Monarch*, the first seagoing warship to carry her guns in turrets.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Laid down in 1866 and completed in June 1869, it carried two turrets, although the inclusion of a forecastle and poop prevented the guns firing fore and aft.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The gun turret was independently invented by the Swedish inventor John Ericsson in America, although his design was technologically inferior to Coles'.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Ericsson designed USS *Monitor* in 1861.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Its most prominent feature was a large cylindrical gun turret mounted amidships above the low-freeboard upper hull, also called the "raft".
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] This extended well past the sides of the lower, more traditionally shaped hull.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] A small armored pilot house was fitted on the upper deck towards the bow, however, its position prevented *Monitor* from firing her guns straight forward.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] One of Ericsson's prime goals in designing the ship was to present the smallest possible target to enemy gunfire.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The turret's rounded shape helped to deflect cannon shot.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] A pair of donkey engines rotated the turret through a set of gears; a full rotation was made in 22.5 seconds during testing on 9 February 1862.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Fine control of the turret proved to be difficult as the engine would have to be placed in reverse if the turret overshot its mark or another full rotation could be made.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Including the guns, the turret weighed approximately 160 long tons (163 t); the entire weight rested on an iron spindle that had to be jacked up using a wedge before the turret could rotate.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The spindle was 9 inches (23 cm) in diameter, which gave it ten times the strength needed in preventing the turret from sliding sideways.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] When not in use, the turret rested on a brass ring on the deck that was intended to form a watertight seal.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] In service, however, this proved to leak heavily, despite caulking by the crew.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The gap between the turret and the deck proved to be a problem as debris and shell fragments entered the gap and jammed the turrets of several *Passaic*-class monitors, which used the same turret design, during the First Battle of Charleston Harbor in April 1863.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Direct hits at the turret with heavy shot also had the potential to bend the spindle, which could also jam the turret.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The turret was intended to mount a pair of 15-inch (380 mm) smoothbore Dahlgren guns, but they were not ready in time and 11-inch (280 mm) guns were substituted.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Each gun weighed approximately 16,000 pounds (7,300 kg).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] *Monitor*'s guns used the standard propellant charge of 15 pounds (6.8 kg) specified by the 1860 ordnance for targets "distant", "near", and "ordinary", established by the gun's designer Dahlgren himself.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] They could fire a 136-pound (61.7 kg) round shot or shell up to a range of 3,650 yards (3,340 m) at an elevation of +15°.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] HMS *Thunderer* represented the culmination of this pioneering work.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] An ironclad turret ship designed by Edward James Reed, it was equipped with revolving turrets that used pioneering hydraulic turret machinery to maneouvre the guns.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] It was also the world's first mastless battleship, built with a central superstructure layout, and became the prototype for all subsequent warships.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] HMS *Devastation* of 1871 was another pivotal design, and led directly to the modern battleship.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] During the late 1850s, the development and implementation of the ironclad warship carried wrought iron armor of considerable thickness.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] This armor was practically immune to both the round cast-iron cannonballs then in use and to the recently developed explosive shell.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The first solution to this problem was effected by Major Sir W.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] His Palliser shot, approved in 1867, was made of cast iron, the head being chilled in casting to harden it, using composite molds with a metal, water cooled portion for the head.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] At times there were defects that led to cracking in the projectiles but these were overcome with time.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Bronze studs were installed into the outside of the projectile so as to engage the rifling grooves in the gun barrel.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] At the Battle of Angamos (8 October 1879) the Chilean ironclad warships fired twenty 250-pound-Palliser gunshots against the Peruvian monitor *Huáscar*, with devastating results.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] It was the first time that such piercing shells were used in actual combat.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] These chilled iron shots proved very effective against wrought iron armor, but were not serviceable against compound and steel armor, which was first introduced in the 1880s.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] A new departure therefore had to be made, and forged steel rounds with points hardened by water took the place of the Palliser shot.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] At first, these forged-steel rounds were made of ordinary carbon steel, but as armor improved in quality, the projectiles followed suit.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] From the 1890s onwards, cemented steel armor became commonplace, initially only on the thicker armor of warships.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] To combat this, the projectile was formed of steel—forged or cast—containing both nickel and chromium.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Another change was the introduction of a soft metal cap over the point of the shell – so called "Makarov tips" invented by Russian admiral Stepan Makarov.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] This "cap" increased penetration by cushioning some of the impact shock and preventing the armor-piercing point from being damaged before it struck the armor face, or the body of the shell from shattering.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] It could also help penetration from an oblique angle by keeping the point from deflecting away from the armor face .
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Increased armor penetration became possible when projectile velocities of 800 m/s (2,600 ft/s) were obtained as smokeless powder propellants replaced gunpowder around the turn of the 20th century.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Underwater hull damage possible with torpedoes encouraged development of small, inexpensive torpedo boats capable of sinking the largest warships.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] By the end of the 19th century, all warships required a defensive battery of quick-firing guns capable of hitting fast, maneuverable torpedo boats.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The Royal Navy first introduced the quick-firing 4.7-inch gun in HMS *Sharpshooter* in 1889, and the quick-firing 6-inch MK 1 in HMS *Royal Sovereign*, launched 1891.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Other navies followed suit; the French Navy installed quick-firing weapons on its ships completed in 1894–95.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Quick-firing guns were a key characteristic of the pre-dreadnought battleship, the dominant design of the 1890s.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The quick-firing guns, while unable to penetrate thick armour, were intended to destroy the superstructure of an opposing battleship, start fires, and kill or distract the enemy's gun crews.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Quick-firing guns were initially breech-loading weapons firing ammunition small enough to be loaded by hand.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Later substitution of brass cartridges for silk powder bags allowed increased rates of fire using sliding wedge breech blocks.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Increasing mechanization ultimately enabled similar rates of fire from naval artillery calibers up to 8 inches (20 cm).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] When gunnery ranges increased dramatically in the late 19th century, it was no longer a simple matter of calculating the proper aim point, given the flight times of the shells.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Increasingly sophisticated mechanical calculators were employed for proper gunlaying, typically with various spotters and distance measures being sent to a central plotting station deep within the ship.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] There the fire direction teams fed in the location, speed and direction of the ship and its target, as well as various adjustments for Coriolis effect, weather effects on the air, and other adjustments.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The resulting directions, known as a firing solution, would then be fed back out to the turrets for laying.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] If the rounds missed, an observer could work out how far they missed by and in which direction, and this information could be fed back into the computer along with any changes in the rest of the information and another shot attempted.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The situation for naval fire control was highly complex, due to the need to control the firing of several guns at once.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] In naval engagements both the firing guns and target are moving, and the variables are compounded by the greater distances and times involved.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Rudimentary naval fire control systems were first developed around the time of World War I.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Arthur Pollen and Frederic Charles Dreyer independently developed the first such systems.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Pollen began working on the problem after noting the poor accuracy of naval artillery at a gunnery practice near Malta in 1900.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Pollen aimed to produce a combined mechanical computer and automatic plot of ranges and rates for use in centralised fire control.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] To obtain accurate data of the target's position and relative motion, Pollen developed a plotting unit (or plotter) to capture this data.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] He added a gyroscope to allow for the yaw of the firing ship.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Again this required substantial development of the, at the time, primitive gyroscope to provide continuous reliable correction.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Trials were carried out in 1905 and 1906, which although completely unsuccessful showed promise.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] He was encouraged in his efforts by the rapidly rising figure of Admiral Jackie Fisher, Admiral Arthur Knyvet Wilson and the Director of Naval Ordnance and Torpedoes (DNO), John Jellicoe.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Pollen continued his work, with tests carried out on Royal Navy warships intermittently.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Meanwhile, a group led by Dreyer designed a similar system.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Although both systems were ordered for new and existing ships of the Royal Navy, the Dreyer system eventually found most favour with the Navy in its definitive Mark IV* form.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The addition of director control facilitated a full, practicable fire control system for World War I ships, and most RN capital ships were so fitted by mid 1916.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The director was high up over the ship where operators had a superior view over any gunlayer in the turrets.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] It was also able to co-ordinate the fire of the turrets so that their combined fire worked together.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] This improved aiming and larger optical rangefinders improved the estimate of the enemy's position at the time of firing.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The system was eventually replaced by the improved "Admiralty Fire Control Table" for ships built after 1927.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Significant gunnery developments occurred in the late 1890s and the early 1900s, culminating with the launch of the revolutionary HMS *Dreadnought* in 1906.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Sir Percy Scott was given command of HMS *Scylla* in 1896, where he was able to implement his new theories on gunnery, scoring the unprecedented success of 80% during the 1897 gunnery trials.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] This was totally unprecedented, as the average in the Royal Navy was just 28%.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Scott noted that night time signalling between ships in the fleet was slow and inaccurate.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] He addressed this in two ways: he devised training aids and put his signallers under instruction and he devised a new more effective flashing lamp.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The new efficiency of his ship's signalling was adopted by the whole Mediterranean fleet.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] He devised a new sub-calibre gun which involved fitting a one-inch-calibre rifled barrel inside the barrel of the main armament but which used the main gun's controls.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] He also came up with new sights employing telescope optics and new training targets.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] In the Navy's 1901 prize firing, *Terrible* achieved the same score of 80%, and Scott's gunnery practices were adopted by other ships in the fleet.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Later, Scott taught at the naval gunnery school at Whale Island, Hampshire. a largely honorary role which he held until promotion to flag rank in 1905.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The development of the torpedo meant that it became necessary to engage an enemy at ranges outside torpedo range.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] This in turn meant that the old system whereby a gunlayer in each turret pointed and fired the turret guns independently could no longer be expected to achieve a significant hit rate on an opposing ship.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Scott was instrumental in encouraging the development and installation of director firing, a system whereby the guns were all pointed, elevated and fired from a single point, usually at the top of the foremast.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] By firing all the guns simultaneously it was possible to observe the simultaneous splashes produced and correct the aim visually.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] As battle ranges were pushed out to an unprecedented 6,000 yards (5,500 m), the distance was great enough to force gunners to wait for the shells to arrive before applying corrections for the next salvo.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] A related problem was that the shell splashes from the more numerous smaller weapons tended to obscure the splashes from the bigger guns.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Either the smaller-calibre guns would have to hold their fire to wait for the slower-firing heavies, losing the advantage of their faster rate of fire, or it would be uncertain whether a splash was due to a heavy or a light gun, making ranging and aiming unreliable.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] First Sea Lord Sir John Fisher pushed through the Board of Admiralty a decision to arm the next battleship with 12-inch guns and that it would have a speed no less than 21 knots (39 km/h).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The result was HMS *Dreadnought*, which rendered all previous ships immediately obsolete on its launch in 1906.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The ship mounted the 45-calibre BL 12-inch Mark X gun in five twin gun turrets.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] These could deliver a broadside of a maximum of eight guns and could be elevated up to +13.5°.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] They fired 850-pound (390 kg) projectiles at a muzzle velocity of 2,725 ft/s (831 m/s); at 13.5°, this provided a maximum range of 16,450 m (17,990 yd) with armour-piercing (AP) 2 crh shells.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] At 16° elevation, the range was extended to 20,435 yd (18,686 m) using the more aerodynamic, but slightly heavier 4 crh AP shells.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The rate of fire of these guns was one to two rounds per minute.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Within five years of the commissioning of *Dreadnought*, a new generation of more powerful "super-dreadnoughts" was being built.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The arrival of the super-dreadnought is commonly believed to have started with the British *Orion* class.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] What made them 'super' was the unprecedented 2,000-ton jump in displacement, the introduction of the heavier 13.5-inch (343 mm) gun, and the placement of all the main armament on the centerline.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] In the four years between *Dreadnought* and *Orion*, displacement had increased by 25%, and weight of broadside had doubled.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] In comparison to the rapid advancement of the preceding half-century, naval artillery changed comparatively little through World War I and World War II.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Battleships remained similar to *Dreadnought*, torpedo boats evolved into destroyers, and ships of intermediate size were called cruisers.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] All ship types became larger as the calibre of heavy guns increased (to a maximum of 46 centimetres (18.1 in) in the *Yamato*-class battleships), but the number of guns carried remained similar.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Smaller ships used smaller-calibre weapons which were also used on battleships as the defensive secondary armament.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Although naval artillery had been designed to perform within the classical broadside tactics of the age of sail, World War I demonstrated the need for naval artillery mounts capable of greater elevation for defending against aircraft.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] High-velocity naval artillery intended to puncture side armor at close range was theoretically capable of hitting targets miles away with the aid of fire control directors; but the maximum elevation of guns mounted within restrictive armored casemates prevented reaching those ranges.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The QF 4 inch Mk V naval gun was one of the first artillery pieces to be adapted as an anti-aircraft gun and mounted on ships for defence.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] It was first used in 1914 as a secondary armament on *Arethusa*-class cruisers in a high-angle anti-aircraft role.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Most naval artillery on ships built after World War I was capable of elevating to at least 45°, and some guns as large as 8 inches (20 cm) were capable of elevating to 70° for potential use against aircraft.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The Japanese used their large caliber guns for anti-aircraft defense when employing San Shiki "beehive" shells.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Dual purpose guns were devised to protect ships against both torpedo boats and aircraft, and for WWII they comprised the primary armament on frigates and destroyers, and the secondary armament on cruisers and battleships.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The light anti-aircraft artillery typically consisted of autocannons such as the Bofors 40 mm anti-aircraft guns and 65 single Oerlikon 20 mm cannon.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] As destroyers began to assume ASW roles to include protection of the fleet from submarines, they were fitted with high-angle depth charge mortars (called Y-guns, K-guns or squid).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Battleships were used in support of amphibious operations since the late 19th century in the form of naval bombardment.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Under international law such bombardments are regulated by the general law of war and the "Bombardment by Naval Forces in Time of War (Hague Convention IX)"; 18 October 1907.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] At the beginning of World War I, its principal practitioner was the Royal Navy.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] During the War RN ships fired against targets at Gallipoli, the Salonika front and along the Belgian Coast.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] In the Aegean, the problems were not especially challenging, and enemy coastal defences (forts, shore-batteries etc.) were fairly unsophisticated; but along the Belgian Coast the Germans constructed an extensive, well-equipped and well-coordinated system of gun-batteries to defend the coast.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Ports, such as Ostend and Zeebrugge were of major importance to the U-boat campaign and were frequently bombarded by British monitors operating from Dover and Dunkirk.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The Royal Navy continually advanced their technology and techniques necessary to conduct effective bombardments in the face of the German defenders—firstly refining aerial reconnaissance techniques, then experimenting with night-bombardment and moving on to adopt indirect fire.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Finally, in the summer of 1918, monitors were equipped with Gyro Director Training gear, which effectively provided the Director with a gyro-stabilised Artificial Line of Sight, and thereby enabled a ship to carry out Indirect Bombardment while underway.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] This was a very significant advance, and established a firm foundation for naval bombardment as practiced by the Royal Navy and United States Navy during World War II.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The practice reached its zenith during World War II, when the availability of man-portable radio systems and sophisticated relay networks allowed forward observers to transmit targeting information and provide almost instant accuracy reports—once troops had landed.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Battleships, cruisers and destroyers would pound shore installations, sometimes for days, in the hope of reducing fortifications and attriting defending forces.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Obsolete battleships unfit for combat against other ships were often used as floating gun platforms expressly for this purpose.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] However, given the relatively primitive nature of the fire control computers and radar of the era combined with the high velocity of naval gunfire, accuracy was poor until troops landed and were able to radio back reports to the ship.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Naval gunfire could reach as far as 20 miles (32 km) inland, and was often used to supplement land-based artillery.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The heavy-calibre guns of some eighteen battleships and cruisers were used to stop German Panzer counterattack at Salerno.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Naval gunfire was used extensively throughout Normandy, although initially the surprise nature of the landings themselves precluded a drawn-out bombardment which could have reduced the Atlantic Wall defences sufficiently, a process that fell to specialist armoured vehicles instead.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The effective range of naval artillery evolved over the course of its history.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 2. medium range: considered typical for naval engagement.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 3. long range: single hits inflicting some damage upon enemy ships were considered possible, though accuracy was expected to be very low, at 1–3%.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] "culverin, a long-barreled naval canon widely used in the 15th and 16th centuries, featured effective operating distance probably no more than 350 yards".
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] "most battles were fought at point-blank range, no further than a pistol shot and sometimes muzzle-to-muzzle".
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 6. in the late 17th century "effective range for the heavy cannon" was perhaps 400 yards.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 20-30 yards was typical or preferred range in the 18th century, effective range was 280 yards, and extreme range about a mile.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] In practice the gunners waited until the distance was 100 yards The English captains preferred to close at "pistol shot range" (some 20 yards) before opening fire.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] "most naval battles were fought at musket shot (100 yards) or pistol shot (50 yards)" In 1812, USS *Constitution* engaged HMS *Guerriere* at 25–50 yards.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] "before 1850 ... the most effective and preferred distance was 100 yards – known as the half pistol".
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 12. in the early 19th century maximum effective range was some 400 yards.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] "few hundred yards" were "realistic ranges" during the 1860s.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] "Cast-iron smooth bore guns firing solid shot with a theoretical maximum hitting range of 1,000 yards were still the rule".
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] During the American civil war warships were considered relatively safe from enemy fire at a range of 1,200-1,300 yards.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Theoretical ranges of American naval smoothbores as defined by the US Navy in 1866 ranged from 1,756 (32-pounder) to 2,100 yards (XV-inch shell).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 14. in 1882 a British naval expert and MP claimed in the Commons that "the effective fire of guns will be delivered within rather beyond a range of 500 yards".
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 15. in 1870 during a practice at 1,000 yards 3 British ironclads landed 1 hit out of 12 rounds against a ship-sized rock.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] In the 1870s the French naval planners considered protection armor against longest hits from a distance of 2,000 yards.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] "Ships were not expected to engage at more than 2,000 yards" in the 1880s.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] British naval expert and MP claimed that "the practice of naval guns in action at distances exceeding 1,000 yards" was uncertain and there was no sense adjusting powder capacity to go beyond that range.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 200–300 yards was considered point blank range at the turn of the century.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] "distances of up to 1,000 yards became possible" by the mid-1890s.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Until 1904 the British navy premier gunnery exercise, the Annual Prize Firings, were held at 1,400–1,600 yards.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 18. out of 8,000 rounds fired by American warships against stationary targets at a distance of 0.5–3 miles during a battle of the Spanish–American War there were 129 hits (ca 1.5%).
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Other sources note 2% accuracy at 2,000 yards during the same war.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 19. in the very early 20th century 4,000 yards was considered short distance in the British Navy.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 21. under favorable conditions centrally controlled accurate salvo was deemed possible at 8,000 yards and under very favorable ones at 10,000 yards.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 22. in 1913 the Home Fleet commander issued orders which envisaged "decisive range" of 8,000–10,000.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] German commanders were instructed to fight at 7,000-9,000 yards.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 23. in 1913 the Home Fleet commander issued orders which envisaged opening fire at 15,000 weather permitting.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] During the Battle of Jutland of 1914 a 3% accuracy was achieved at a distance of 16,000 yards.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] In 1915 20,000 yards was considered extreme and basically theoretical range.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] In the early 1920s the US Navy produced a table which estimated average hit ratio for battleship gunfire; distances of 10,000 yards and below were not even considered.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 25. in the interwar period 15% was "realistic battle expectation" at 15,000 yards.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] US Navy practice with 3 battleships each firing 56 rounds at 12,800 range against a battleship-representative target led to conclusion that at this distance "opening salvos" should produce 7% accuracy.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The US Navy table of the early 1920s estimated that for 18,000 yards the hit ratio was to be at 4.2%, for 16,000 yards at 6.2%, for 14,000 yards at 8.9% and for 12,000 yards at 12.3%.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] *Hood* firing at *Bismarck* achieved 3,5% accuracy at 20,000 yards; *Bismarck* firing at *Hood* achieved 5% at the same distance.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] However, during training exercises of 1930 US Navy battleships used to open fire at the extreme range of 35,000 yards; it is not clear what the hit ratio was.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] 31. the longest hits were recorded in 1940 by *Scharnhorst* firing at *Glorious* and by *Warspite* firing at *Giulio Cesare*, in both cases the distance was some 26,000 yards.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The US Navy considered 28,000 yards "maximum effective range of battleship guns" if without aerial spotting.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] By the mid-20th century, aircraft began to replace naval artillery as more effective weapons against ships, especially during World War II.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] This was particularly true of the Pacific Ocean theater where there ended up being far fewer engagements between surface combatants, including only two "battleship-versus-battleship" meetings.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Most of the decisive battles in the Pacific were carrier-versus-carrier, included Coral Sea, the first battle in which the opposing ships neither sighted nor fired directly upon one another, followed by Midway, the Eastern Solomons, and the Santa Cruz Islands in 1942; and the Philippine Sea in 1944.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Larger surface combatants (cruisers, battleships) thus employed their large caliber naval guns mostly for shore bombardment.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Also, the Japanese fired San Shiki "beehive" shells for anti-aircraft defense, as did the German battleship *Tirpitz*, but this largely proved ineffective against attacking aircraft.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Naval artillery calibers greater than 130 mm (5.1 in) were not installed on most new ships after World War II.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] With the progression of ship design away from heavy caliber guns, nearly all main gun armaments developed since then are of dual-purpose nature.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Ships who remained in service equipped with old large-caliber artillery were used only for naval gunfire support, as the anti-ship missile has supplanted naval guns for ship-versus-ship combat.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] USS *Missouri*, the last active battleship with large-caliber guns (16 in (410 mm)) was decommissioned in 1992.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Submarines shed their deck guns as a handicap in modern naval tactics.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] After World War II, guided missiles were retrofitted to certain surface combatants.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Modern cruisers, destroyers, and frigates often carry 1-2 dual-purpose guns, as a backup to missile systems for anti-aircraft defense and capable of land fire support, ranging from 3 inch to 5.1 inch (76 to 130 mm) calibre.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Many modern warships also carry a Close-in weapon system such as the 20 mm Phalanx CIWS as a last ditch short-range defence against anti-ship missiles or aircraft that got through the other defense systems.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Modern naval artillery is nevertheless still capable of impressive performances.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] For example, the Italian 127 mm (~5 inch) Otobreda 127/54 Compact can fire 40 rounds a minute at a range of over 23 kilometres (25,153 yd), or up to 100 kilometres (62 mi) when using rocket-boosted, terminal guided "Vulcano GLR" rounds.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] Smaller, multi-role vessels are also seeing a resurgence.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] The Ukrainian Gyurza M-Class Gunboat is an example, armed with 2 turrets built by Mykolayiv Mechanical Repair Plant.
[src:naval-artillery/naval-artillery-p02] In the early 21st century the use of railguns mounted on ships is under development and study.
